      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk level.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented V&V procedures, release notes, and regression test suites. FDA in-house scripts used for post-processing are version-controlled in a validated software environment compliant with 21 CFR Part 11 requirements. Required gradation 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and benchmark problems from NAFEMS benchmark suite confirm correct implementation of linear hexahedral and tetrahedral elements used in the screw-rod construct model. Analytical solutions for cantilever bending and torsion match FEA outputs to within 0.5%, satisfying gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. The Richardson extrapolation-based Grid Convergence Index (GCI) is below 2% for peak von Mises stress and construct stiffness quantities of interest, confirming discretization error is adequately controlled at gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Linear static analysis with a direct sparse solver (PARDISO) is employed. Residual norms are monitored and fall below 1e-8 for all load steps. No iterative solver convergence issues were observed across the ensemble of 11 model instances, satisfying gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Model setup, boundary condition application, and post-processing were independently reviewed by a second analyst following a documented simulation plan. Discrepancies identified during review were resolved prior to final result extraction. Peer review log is archived in the project quality management system, satisfying gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic continuum mechanics with frictional contact at the screw-rod interface is judged appropriate for the sub-yield loading regime of the F1717 protocol. Assumptions regarding bone block rigidity and polyaxial screw head kinematics are documented and consistent with published literature for this test configuration. Gradation 3 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (titanium alloy Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, nu=0.34) are sourced from ASTM F136 and confirmed by manufacturer certification. Geometric inputs are derived from CMM measurements of the actual test specimens with documented uncertainty. Friction coefficients at the screw-rod interface are based on published tribology data for titanium on titanium under dry conditions, satisfying gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from production lots were tested across two independent laboratories. Sample traceability to manufacturing records is confirmed. The sample size provides adequate statistical basis for mean and variability characterization at gradation 3, consistent with ASME V&V 40 guidance for medical device validation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single axial compressive load magnitude per the standard F1717 protocol. Variation in load magnitude or load angle was not explored, limiting the breadth of condition coverage to gradation 2. This shortfall is acknowledged; risk acceptance is documented in the decision record. A waiver was granted by the assessment team given the standardized nature of the F1717 protocol."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs are mapped directly to experimentally measured specimen geometry and material lot certifications. Applied loads and boundary conditions in the simulation replicate the F1717 fixture kinematics as confirmed by fixture drawing review. Input parameter equivalency is formally documented in the simulation plan, satisfying gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield load predictions from the FEA ensemble are compared against experimental measurements using the validation metric defined in ASME V&V 10.1. The area validation metric (Av) is computed with experimental uncertainty bounds. All 11 specimen comparisons fall within the defined acceptance band, satisfying gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield load under F1717 compression-bending are the primary quantities of interest for the pre-market submission. These quantities are directly linked to the clinical risk question of implant mechanical integrity during physiological loading in lumbar spinal fusion. Relevance to the submission decision is formally established in the claim statement, satisfying gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the ASTM F1717 test configuration that is the regulatory standard for spinal implant mechanical performance. The FEA model geometry, loading, and boundary conditions are matched to the physical test, and the validation domain overlaps substantially with the intended submission use. Gradation 3 is satisfied."
    }
